         <p class="- topic/p ">The system will switch over to
battery operation if the rectifier mains becomes unavailable. For
example if:<ul class="- topic/ul ">
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">There is a voltage dip (power sag) on the rectifier mains.</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">The rectifier mains voltage and/or frequency is outside the
tolerance range.</p>
               </li>
            </ul>The switch over to battery operation is automatic without interruption.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">In battery operation the batteries are being discharged to supply
the load. The battery voltage drops as a function of the duration
and the battery output current.<ph platform="PxW" class="- topic/ph "> The AC output voltage
is kept constant by the inverter.</ph> An alarm will activate when
the batteries are almost discharged. If the mains returns (by any
means and is within the tolerance range) the system will automatically
switch back to <ph platform="PxW WxW" class="- topic/ph ">normal operation</ph>
            <ph platform="SDC" class="- topic/ph ">float charge or boost charge</ph>.</p>
         <p platform="PxW" class="- topic/p ">
            <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">For systems with bypass: </b>If the mains does not return before
the batteries are discharged, the system will automatically change
to bypass operation (if the bypass mains is available and within the
tolerance range).</p>
         <p platform="PxW" class="- topic/p ">If the batteries have been
fully discharged and both the rectifier mains and bypass mains are
unavailable, the system will turn off to avoid deep discharge of the
batteries.</p>
         <p platform="PxW" class="- topic/p ">
            <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">For systems with manual bypass
switches: </b>When the load is supplied by the battery in battery
operation, the manual bypass switch is in <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">Auto</b> position.</p>
